# Review Articles

## Koetzier et al

**Traditional Reconstruction Methods**  
FBP

- pros: FBP computationally efficient, numerically stable  
- cons: suffers from high noise and more artifacts when dose is lowered or larger patients are scanned  
- 

MBIR

- multiple iterations (usually 5\) of back and forward projections between sinogram domain and image domain  
- back projection, generation of artificial sinogram from back-projected image, then artificial sinogram compared with original to reduce noise  
- pros: reduces noise and artifacts compared to FBP  
- cons: most computationally demanding, long reconstruction times (2-4 mins). low-frequency noise seems “plastic” and “blotchy”

HIR

- iterations in sinogram domain, back projection, more iterations in image domain  
- pros: faster than MBIR  
- cons: worse at noise reduction

Questions:

- how exactly does FBP, MBIR, and HIR work?  
  - FBP: filtering \- ramp filter in frequency domain  
  - MBIR: what exactly is modeled besides the CT machine in forward projection? \- nothing. Can DL be used to take over the modeling part? \- unsensical  
  - HIR: what does an iteration in sinogram or image domain do?

**Deep Learning Reconstruction**

- Benefits of DLR (general): lowers image noise and artifacts while preserving spatial resolution and shortening reconstruction time  
- Indirect DLR:   
  1. Sinogram-based: Sinogram optimization → network modifies sinogram before FBP or IR  
  2. Image-based: Image optimization → network modifies image after FBP or IR  
  3. Hybrid frameworks: Sinogram and image optimization  
- commonly CNN-based networks  
- transformer-based and GAN-based have been used: MORE RESEARCH HERE  
- Direct DLR:  
  - sinogram to image, replaced conventional reconstruction techniques  
  - can avoid weaknesses of FBP and IR (artifacts, reconstruction time, image quality…)   
- Data: lower-dose CT data to routine dose (2-4x lower dose) or higher-dose (4-8x lower dose) images  
- Reconstructed image style will match with training data  
- artifact sinogram to clean images can lead to learned artifact reduction  
  - sinogram domain more suitable  
- MAR  
  - hybrid algorithms (remove corrupted sinogram data, introduces new artifacts unlike interpolation, removed by image network)  
  - artifact-free vs. artifact data hard to acquire → synthetic artifacts added, might not accurately model real artifacts  
  - DL-MAR superior to non-DL algs in peak SNR and SSIM  
- FDA-approved vendors  
  - True Fidelity  
    - CNN-based direct DLR  
    - lower-dose sinograms to higher-dose images (FBP-reconstructed)  
    - achieved noise reduction and faster reconstruction (GE Healthcare’s video)  
  - AiCE  
    - indirect DLR in image domain  
    - lower-dose HIR images to routine dose MBIR images  
    - MBIR GT allows for artifact reduction  
    - filters sinogram, reconstructs initial image, CNN to improve image  
    - 44 sec reconstruction time  
    - Photo from PIQE (Canon) shows benefits of 3D![][image2]  
  - Precise Image  
    - CNN  
    - routine-dose FBP images, **simulated sinograms with simulated noise**  
  - ClariCT  
    - noise-simulated FBP to original FBP  
    - trained on over a million images  
    - Nam et al compared subjective image quality on lower-dose chest-scans between ClariCT and HIR, ClariCT superior  
  - PixelShine  
    - algorithms enhanced with PixelShine superior to without  
    - performance in artifact reduction is limited because artifacts such as beam hardening are better corrected in sinogram domain  
  - All proprietary systems → public information rather rare  
- lower-dose CT: DLR excellent in noise reduction, comparable to routine-dose FBP and HIR. dose reduction by 30-71% (DLR vs. FBP) and 50% (DLR vs. FBP)  
- Thin section protocols can reveal more image features (e.g. coronary CT angiography). DLR algs maintained diagnostic image quality compared to thick-section protocols (similar noise magnitude and CNS, superior subjective image quality)  
- Applications:  
  - Abdominal:  
    - low-contrast tissue interfaces   
    - high-strength IR hinders detection of hepatic lesions  
    - Yang: increased subjective image quality DLR vs. HIR, no change detection rates  
    - Other studies: improved objective and subjective image quality & lesion detection to HIR and FBP  
  - Brain:  
    - Image noise and streak artifacts affect image interpretation (gray-white matter differentiation and hemorrhage detection)  
    - both indirect and direct DLR improved image noise, artifact reduction, gray-white matter differentiation  
  - Chest & Cardiac  
    - high-contrast tissues  
    - improved SNR, CNR, sharpness, noise texture  
    - DLR created distortion artifacts → misdiagnosis  
    - **CHALLENGE**: contour delineation of small vessels for lower doses → DLR can solve problem  
  - Pediatric:  
    - low radiation crucial  
    - DLR lower-dose cardiac CT angiography for various illnesses: improved noise, SNR, CNR, subjective image quality  
    - object detectability and detection accuracy (chest, abdominal, pelvic) superior to other algs: best noise, sharpness, object conspicuity, radiologist confidence  
    - potential dose reduction to HIR: 52%  
  - Results:  
    - image quality improvements  
    - no changes in diagnostic quality and lesion detection rates (brain, chest & cardiac, abdominal)  
    - increased detection accuracy, diagnostic confidence, and image quality for pediatric while dose reduction  
- Challenges & Prospects:  
  - hallucination: noise interpreted as missing object (pot. false positive) → inaccurate anatomic features  
  - inverse hallucination: removes parts of the image incorrectly (pot. false negative)Training data crucial:   
    - large  
    - unbiased  
    - heterogenous  
    - variability: CT scanner models, clinical conditions, acquisition parameters(, demographics?)  
    - include challenging images (e.g. small vessels)  
  - Artifact reduction limited, requires artifact-free vs. artifact-corrupted images, yet to determine which algorithm better for ground truth  
  - bariatric patients: studies needed  
  - phantom data should be leveraged  
  - Sinogram interpretation: sinogram-to diagnosis

**Image Quality Metrics / Facets**

- Hounsfield unit: standardized unit to represent CT values   
  - range in body:  
  - \-1000 (air) appears black in scan, 1000+ (bone) appears white  
  - (µmaterial \- µwater) / µwater  
  - µ attenuation coefficient: how much incident energy beam is weakened by material  
- Noise:  
  - Noise magnitude: stdev of Hounsfield units within a homogenous region of interest  
    - does not capture noise structure  
  - Signal-to-noise ratio (SNR)  
  - Contrast-to-noise ratio (CNR)  
  - noise power spectrum (NPS)  
  - modulation transfer function (MTF)  
  - Artifact Index (AI)  
  - higher objective image quality corresponds to higher subjective image quality  
  - Root mean square deviation (RMSD)

## Szczykutowicz et al

FBP

- cons:  
  - fails to account for realities of CT data acquisition: noise, polychromatic nature of imaging spectrum, finite amount of x-rays, size and shape of detector elements  
  - **noise increases as inverse sqrt of dose or slice thickness** → lower dose traded for a significant increase in noise  
  - photon starvation in obese patients decreases observed attenuation  
  - why is noise a problem? Can interfere with detection of low-contrast lesions (e.g. hypoenhancing liver metastases)  
  - summary:  
    - can’t recognize homogenous regions (could be “smoothed”)  
    - can’t recognize heterogeneous regions (should not be “smoothed”)

IR / MBIR:

- during iterative noise reduction regularization termused to stabilizes solution (limit solution space to solutions that match assumptions)  
- smoothes flat regions (determined using image gradients) → nonlinear (hard to invert)  
- pros:   
  - offset noise increase associated with lowering dose → reduces ionizing radiation → dose reduction \~25%  
- cons:  
  - image gradients depend on contrast levels → low dose drastically reduces image quality because can’t recognize uniform regions, might smooth out low-contrast lesions  
  - leftward shift in NPS (lower frequency noise texture) displeasing for radiologists

# Vocabulary

The **linear attenuation coefficient µ** characterizes the fraction of the incident x-rays beam that is absorbed or scattered per unit’s thickness of the materials. For a uniform object, µ=ln(I0/I)/x

# MRI vs. CT in general

CT (cons):

- radiation causes a slight risk of cancer (1/2000)  
- radiation from CT studies currently being performed may ultimately account for 1.5% to 2% of all cancers in the future

CT (pros): agile, fast scans of all parts of the body in a few seconds, excellent for diagnosing and staging cancer  
MRI (cons): takes long, 20-40 mins, can be agitating for claustrophobic people or children  
MRI (pros): can detect cancer types invisible to CT, good for soft tissue

  - Dual-energy computed tomography (DECT) uses different energy spectrum x-ray beams for differentiating materials with similar attenuation at a certain energy.   
  - Compared with single-energy CT, it provides images with better diagnostic performance and a potential reduction of contrast agent and radiation doses  
    - Photoelectric effect for low energy beams

    - reveal different atomic numbers → distinguish between density and atomic composition

**Perfusion CT**

- Why CT? CT is faster, cheaper, more accessible and produces less acoustic noise than MRI  
  - Metrics:  
    - relative cerebral blood flow (rCBF):   
    - relative cerebral blood volume (rCBV)  
    - mean transit time (MTT): Value of   
    - Time to Max (TMAX): Information about  
    - Central Volume Principle: CBV / MTT \= CBF  
    - TMAX and MTT are most sensitive to hemodynamic changes  
    - cerebral perfusion pressure (CPP)  
  - Two Models: Maximum slope and Deconvolution  
    - Maximum slope is easy to use, assumes no venous outflow (clinically unachievable)

![][image4]

- Background  
  - non-contrast CT can identify infarcted brain tissue (ischemic core), Perfusion CT can identify dying tissue (ischemic penumbra) which is potentially salvageable. This influences treatment  
    - MRI is more sensitive to the early parenchymal changes of infarction, its clinical application limited by low accessibility when assessment and intervention has to be performed in timely fashion  
    - Stage 1 hemodynamic compromise  
    - CPP decreases, brain’s autoregulative ability causes vasodilation to maintain constant CBF  
    - CPP below 40 mm Hg: vasodilation reaches limits, CBF decreases linearly  
    - To compensate, extraction of oxygen from the blood is increased: Stage 2 hemodynamic failure  
    - CPP above 140 mm Hg: vasoconstriction reaches limits, CBF increases lienarly  
    - Stage 2 hemodynamic failure

    Applications

    - Microcirculation imaging  
    - acute stroke, chronic steno-occlusive disease, vasospasm, brain death, brain tumor, and other neuropsychiatric disorders  
  - Methods  
    - based on tracer kinetic model, like MRI Perfusion  
    - First Pass Technique: Monitor changes in tracer density over time

![][image5]

- semi-quantitative measurement of hemodynamic parameters  
  - uses tracer  
    - diffusion magnetic resonance imaging can identify dead brain tissue, CT perfusion imaging can help identify dying brain tissue  
    - CT perfusion in ischemic stroke has become established in most centers with stroke services as an important adjunct, along with CT angiography (CTA), to conventional unenhanced CT brain imaging.  
    - brain functioning  
  - Problems:  
    - extreme low dose required due to longer radiation exposure → high noise, DLR could help  
    - head movement with ischemic stroke patients  
      - Motion artifacts  
    - Barrow’s Institute: Scan time is less than one minute, and postprocessing requires **5 to 15 minutes** depending on the user’s proficiency.  
    - Perfusion CT of Head can take **25 mins**  
    - “Time is Brain”  
  - Deep Learning Applications  
    - Motion artifact reduction   
    - acquisition time reduction  
- CT angiography

**Artifacts**  
beam-hardening

- easier attenuation of low-energy photons in x-ray beam (polychromatic)  
- causes varying calculated absorption rates, infers varying density for various thicknesses of the same density material

![][image6]

- shifts the measured beam energy distribution to the right (increase in mean beam energy) → “hardening”  
- conceptually similar to high-pass filter  
- streaking artifacts  
  - dark streaking bands positioned between two dense objects  
  - increased beam hardening along longer axes of dense object → appears as dark bands  
- cupping artifacts  
  - what you see in image: interpreted attenuation and assigned Hu are lower towards thicker regions than would lead to uniform density reconstruction  
- partial volume artifacts  
- 

Photon Starvation

- caused by high-density material like metal implants that absorb beam  
- results in severe dark bands  
- strong noise around highly attenuating objects  
- Solution: Tube current increase → higher dose

Motion Artifacts

Undersampling

- too large of an interval between projections
